# 2. Critical Rename Safety Rules

## 2.1 Never perform a blind global replacement

Do not execute operations equivalent to:

```text
Replace every "iis" with "iap"
Replace every "IIS" with "IaP"
```

This is prohibited.

The letters `iis` may occur inside unrelated words, identifiers, file contents, binary artifacts, dependency names, URLs, or external product names.

Examples that must not be changed merely because they contain similar letters include:

```text
this
missing
permissions
commission
submission
dismiss
Microsoft IIS
third-party package identifiers
external URLs
generated lockfile integrity values
hashes
binary content
```

Only rename an occurrence after confirming that it refers specifically to this project, its specification, its packages, its commands, or its generated artifacts.

## 2.2 Classify every occurrence

Before editing, classify every occurrence of `IIS`, `iis`, or related naming into one of these categories:

### Category A — Project-specific and must be renamed

Examples:

* `@iis/sdk`
* `iis.dev/v1`
* `infrastructure.iis.yaml`
* `IISDocument`
* “IIS specification”
* `iis validate`
* `iis_create_model`

### Category B — Legacy compatibility and must temporarily remain

Examples:

* Legacy CLI wrapper
* Legacy API-version parser
* Migration fixtures
* Compatibility schemas
* Deprecation documentation
* Old file-extension discovery
* Legacy MCP aliases

### Category C — External or unrelated and must not be changed

Examples:

* Microsoft Internet Information Services
* Third-party package names
* External URLs
* Quoted historical sources
* Standards or products that happen to use IIS

### Category D — Incidental substring and must not be changed

Examples:

* Words containing the character sequence `iis`
* Hashes
* Integrity values
* Generated source maps
* Encoded content

### Category E — Generated or vendored content

Do not edit directly.

Regenerate it from canonical sources where necessary.

## 2.3 Maintain an explicit allowlist

Create:

```text
docs/migrations/iis-to-iap-allowlist.yaml
```

Every intentional remaining occurrence of the old name must include:

* File
* Line or pattern
* Category
* Reason
* Removal version, when applicable

The repository must have an automated check that fails when an unclassified project-specific old-name occurrence is introduced.

## 2.4 Rename semantics, not arbitrary text

Prefer:

* TypeScript AST-aware symbol renaming
* Package manifest parsing
* JSON/YAML parsing
* Schema-aware migration
* Exact path mapping
* Exact command mapping
* Exact namespace mapping

Avoid broad regular-expression replacement across the repository.

## 2.5 Keep the rename separate from feature development

The rename pull requests must not:

* Add new provider capabilities
* Change planner semantics
* Change resource schemas except for naming/version migration
* Refactor unrelated code
* Change security policy behavior
* Change cost calculations
* Modify deployment behavior
* Add new roadmap features

If a defect is discovered during the rename, document it separately unless it directly blocks the rename.

